metadata.name: Sansuhwa #7
metadata.description: Once upon a time, in a house in an oriental village, you can see beautiful nature when you look at the window. This painting of nature is called "Sansuhwa." You can see the sun or the moon, the mountains, the sea, and the forest, but sometimes you can only see a part of them. And what you see in the bottom right is the way that Asian painting usually signs paintings. Usually, it is written in Chinese characters, but I made it specially in Korean.

metadata.name: Evolution of Aesthetics #6
metadata.description:
In this work, I aimed to emphasize that 'Evolution of Aesthetics' highlights the concept that time itself functions as an artist, influencing and shaping the artwork as it ages, ultimately contributing to its final beauty.

Every stain on the paper, every touch of the physical work in someone's hands, and every crack in the canvas become vibrant markers of time, complementing and adding depth to the artwork, rather than diminishing it. Through this rich and vivid evolution, the artwork becomes a story of life and time, where the passage of time is not destructive but rather a necessary catalyst for creating something fresh and extraordinary.

'Evolution of Aesthetics' offers a glimpse into art as an organic entity that breathes and grows through history. What may initially appear as damage becomes a vital element in the narrative that celebrates the beauty of the artistic process, its continual change, and transformation. 


Options:

- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 'd' to save a hi-res PNG image

Created using p5.js
Bajiru, October 2023.

metadata.name: System β #222
metadata.description:
α -> β is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

_
press [1] -> β 
press [2] -> β⁰　 
press [3] -> β¹
-
Press [s] in live view to save as PNG.
Press [d] in live view to save as hi-res PNG.
-
If you need your collection in SVG format, feel free to DM me.

metadata.name: Vertical World #60
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.

metadata.name: Influence no.3:Auras #105
metadata.description:
The third set of the “Influence” series implies the creation of an abstract artwork based on algorithms and colors. Each of the color waves with different orientations next to each other creates an aura state that reminds of abstract acrylic paintings with spatula technique. Various densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 8 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

note:
I highly recommend that you make sure you have enough RAM space and use the Chrome browser or Opera to view the animation in the best possible way. Rendering may take several minutes due to the high density of the artwork.

Made with p5js.
